	     Washington - President Donald Trump's former campaign chair Paul Manafort and a business associate were told to surrender to federal officials on Monday in the probe into Russia's attempts to tilt the 2016 presidential vote in Trump's favour, the New York Times reported. There was no word on what charges have been filed by special counsel Robert Mueller, the former FBI director leading the Russia probe. The Times said Manafort and his longtime associate Rick Gates were told to surrender to federal authorities.  Manafort managed Trump's presidential campaign between June and August 2016. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  